    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Constructing-triangles">
        <title>Constructing triangles</title>
        <introduction>
                    <p>
                    A triangle is a basic shape with three sides and three angles. The three sides of a triangle can have different lengths, and the angles can vary in size, but the sum of the angles in any triangle is always  <m>180^\circ</m>.    
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Types of Triangles
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Triangles can be classified based on angles and sides. 
                    </p>
                                           
                    <p>
                      (i) Classification of triangles Based on Sides
                    </p>
                       <sidebyside>
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Scalene Triangle.
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                Equilateral Triangle. 
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Isosceles Triangle.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                    <image source="/tt1.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                     </sidebyside>
                     

                    <p>
                        (ii) Classification of triangles Based on angles
                    </p>

                     <sidebyside>
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Obtuse Triangle.
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Acute triangle
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Right-angled triange.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                    <image source="/2.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                    </sidebyside>

             </introduction>

        <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Equalateral">
            <title>Constructing equalateral triangles</title>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    An equilateral triangle is a triangle that has all its sides equal in length. Also, the three angles of the equilateral triangle are equal to <m>60</m> degrees. The sum of all three angles of an equilateral triangle is equal to <m>180</m> degrees.  
                </p>

                <p>
                   <me>
                    60^\circ +60^\circ +60^\circ =180^\circ.
                   </me>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Thus, it obeys the angle sum property of triangle. 
                </p>

                <p>
                    The shape of an equilateral triangle is regular. The word ‘Equilateral’ is formed by the combination of two words, i.e., “Equi” meaning equal and “Lateral” meaning sides. An equilateral triangle is also called a regular polygon or regular triangle since all its sides are equal.
                </p>

                <image source="/et.png">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                </image>
            </introduction>
            
